1x, https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_author_avatar_small_2x/public/2017-10/author-profile-default.jpg.webp?h=6386ac74\u0026itok=H2VWJd8e 2x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 420px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":120,\"height\":120}],\"caption\":\"\",\"url\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_author_avatar_small/public/2017-10/author-profile-default.jpg.webp?h=6386ac74\u0026itok=yMcB1DYB\"}}],\"contributingAuthors\":[],\"products\":[],\"paragraphs\":[{\"bundle\":\"rich_text\",\"content\":\"\u003cp\u003eHardcoded credentials—API keys, secrets, or tokens located directly in a browser extension’s JavaScript—rank among the most significant security oversights in modern development. Once published, these secrets are exposed to anyone who cares to look; an attacker needs only inspect the extension package to extract them. From there, the attacker can craft malicious requests—ranging from spamming analytics with bogus events to commandeering paid cloud services, incurring fees, and undermining user privacy. In this blog, we will examine individual examples drawn from popular Chrome extensions, noting the specific code snippets that reveal each secret and explaining the associated risks.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch2\u003eAvast Online Security \u0026amp; Privacy / AVG Online Security\u003c/h2\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe \u003cem\u003eAvast Online Security \u0026amp; Privacy\u003c/em\u003e extension (7,000,000+ users) and \u003cem\u003eAVG Online Security\u003c/em\u003e (600,000+ users) share similar code, each containing a hardcoded Google Analytics 4 (GA4) API secret (Figure 1).\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\"},{\"bundle\":\"image_inline\",\"images\":[{\"sources\":[{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_medium/public/2025-06/1.png.webp?itok=JQqCSMnn 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 720px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":565},{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_small/public/2025-06/1.png.webp?itok=gektVvWL 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 420px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":565}],\"caption\":\"Figure 1. Code snippets showing hardcoded Google Analytics 4 (GA4) API secrets.\",\"url\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_small/public/2025-06/1.png.webp?itok=gektVvWL\",\"link\":\"\"}]},{\"bundle\":\"rich_text\",\"content\":\"\u003cp\u003eBecause the secret (GA4_API_SECRET) is appended to the URL, any attacker who discovers it could bombard the GA4 endpoint with spurious events, corrupting metrics or inflating analytics costs. \u003cem\u003eAVG Online Security\u003c/em\u003e reveals a virtually identical pattern in its code. Both extensions demonstrate how embedding a private key in the client code can lead to large-scale data pollution or unauthorized access to analytics resources.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch2\u003eEquatio – Math Made Digital\u003c/h2\u003e\u003cp\u003eWith over 5,000,000 users, \u003cem\u003eEquatio – Math Made Digital\u003c/em\u003e embeds an Azure API key used for speech recognition, as seen in Figure 2.\u003c/p\u003e\"},{\"bundle\":\"image_inline\",\"images\":[{\"sources\":[{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_medium/public/2025-06/2.png.webp?itok=fcaQ4Dk7 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 720px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":356},{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_small/public/2025-06/2.png.webp?itok=MmxOHxPI 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 420px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":356}],\"caption\":\"Figure 2. Embedded Azure API key used for speech recognition.\",\"url\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_small/public/2025-06/2.png.webp?itok=MmxOHxPI\",\"link\":\"\"}]},{\"bundle\":\"rich_text\",\"content\":\"\u003cp\u003eBecause the key resides in window.equatioAzureApiKey, anyone inspecting or debugging the extension can clearly see it. The code snippet shown in Figure 2 shows that \u003cem\u003eEquatio\u003c/em\u003e calls fromSubscription(...) with the key to initialize Microsoft Azure’s speech-to-text service. If a malicious user replays or spams these calls, the developer’s Azure subscription could see inflated costs or usage exhaustion.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch2\u003eAwesome Screen Recorder \u0026amp; Screenshot / Scrolling Screenshot Tool \u0026amp; Screen Capture\u003c/h2\u003e\u003cp\u003eBoth \u003cem\u003eAwesome Screen Recorder \u0026amp; Screenshot\u003c/em\u003e (3,000,000+ users) and \u003cem\u003eScrolling Screenshot Tool \u0026amp; Screen Capture\u003c/em\u003e (400,000+ users) use virtually the same snippet for AWS S3 uploads, exposing the developer’s AWS access key (Figure 3).\u003c/p\u003e\"},{\"bundle\":\"image_inline\",\"images\":[{\"sources\":[{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_medium/public/2025-06/3.png.webp?itok=4cS6XGEL 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 720px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":395},{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_small/public/2025-06/3.png.webp?itok=G0wzg88Z 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 420px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":395}],\"caption\":\"Figure 3. Exposed AWS access key.\",\"url\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_small/public/2025-06/3.png.webp?itok=G0wzg88Z\",\"link\":\"\"}]},{\"bundle\":\"rich_text\",\"content\":\"\u003cp\u003eIn both extensions, the embedded key is used to upload screenshots or images to the developer’s S3 bucket. Because the credentials appear in plain text, an attacker could script uploads to the same bucket—potentially hosting illegal content, pushing malicious files, or even pivoting to other AWS resources if the credentials have broader permissions. Essentially, a few lines of JavaScript here undermine the entire AWS environment’s security posture.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch2\u003eMicrosoft Editor – Spelling \u0026amp; Grammar Checker\u003c/h2\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eMicrosoft Editor\u003c/em\u003e (2,000,000+ users) reveals a telemetry key called StatsApiKey. In the code shown in Figure 4, the extension uses that key to log user data for analytics.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\"},{\"bundle\":\"image_inline\",\"images\":[{\"sources\":[{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_medium/public/2025-06/4.png.webp?itok=FpUGJ8zX 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 720px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":665},{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_small/public/2025-06/4.png.webp?itok=kUfzWjb6 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 420px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":665}],\"caption\":\"Figure 4. Exposed telemetry key.\",\"url\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_small/public/2025-06/4.png.webp?itok=kUfzWjb6\",\"link\":\"\"}]},{\"bundle\":\"rich_text\",\"content\":\"\u003cp\u003eAnyone with this key can generate spoofed telemetry data, polluting Microsoft’s analytics and potentially sabotaging any usage insights the developer relies upon. Worse, if the logging system imposes cost or rate limits, mass abuse can drain resources or lock the developer out of their own analytics suite.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch2\u003eAntidote Connector - InboxSDK\u003c/h2\u003e\u003cp\u003eA significant security risk has been uncovered in over 90 Chrome extensions that use the third-party library \u003cem\u003eInboxSDK\u003c/em\u003e, which contains hardcoded credentials. These credentials, including API keys, are often exposed directly in the source code, leaving the extensions vulnerable to exploitation. For instance, the popular extension \u003cem\u003eAntidote Connector\u003c/em\u003e, with over 1,000,000 users, includes this third-party library for certain Gmail requests. In the example shown in Figure 5, we see how this API key is inserted directly into the header for communication with Google services.\u003c/p\u003e\"},{\"bundle\":\"image_inline\",\"images\":[{\"sources\":[{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_medium/public/2025-06/5.png.webp?itok=D_gMXn3n 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 720px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":357},{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_small/public/2025-06/5.png.webp?itok=wBaS-F9a 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 420px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":357}],\"caption\":\"Figure 5. Exposed Google API key for Gmail requests.\",\"url\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_small/public/2025-06/5.png.webp?itok=wBaS-F9a\",\"link\":\"\"}]},{\"bundle\":\"rich_text\",\"content\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe problem stems from the fact that these hardcoded credentials are accessible to anyone who inspects the extension's code. In the case of InboxSDK, the Google API key is attached to each request using 'x-goog-api-key': googleApiKey. This makes it easy for an attacker to replicate the request headers, potentially allowing them to access or manipulate Gmail data, or even spam Google’s endpoints until the developer’s usage quota is exhausted or blacklisted. Given that this vulnerability exists in over 90 extensions using InboxSDK, the issue poses a wide-reaching threat that extends beyond just a single extension. Antidote Connector has since resolved the flaw in its latest version, removing the hard-coded key and adopting a more secure authentication flow.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch2\u003eWatch2Gether\u003c/h2\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eWatch2Gether\u003c/em\u003e (1,000,000+ users) leaks a Tenor GIF search API key (Figure 6).\u003c/p\u003e\"},{\"bundle\":\"image_inline\",\"images\":[{\"sources\":[{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_medium/public/2025-06/6.png.webp?itok=hMDMswFC 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 720px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":283},{\"srcset\":\"https://www.security.com/sites/default/files/styles/blogs_inline_small/public/2025-06/6.png.webp?itok=y1LRvJbn 1x\",\"media\":\"(min-width: 420px)\",\"type\":\"image/webp\",\"width\":624,\"height\":283}],\"caption\":\"Figure 6.
